The paper deals with graph drawing and planarity, which are core topics in computational geometry (cs.CG). It also involves combinatorial aspects, such as testing whether a graph belongs to a certain class, which falls under discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the practical applications of these concepts, such as analyzing relational data sets, which could be relevant to information retrieval (cs.IR) or databases (cs.DB). Finally, the paper involves algorithmic complexity, as it proves NP-hardness results and describes polynomial-time algorithms, which could be relevant to data structures (cs.DS) and algorithms (cs.AL).
